Cell.Data: A Resource Profile - a statement of use of FHIR. May include constraints on Resources, Terminology Binding Statements, and Extension Definitions
Globally unique Profile Id (Must be a UUID)
A free text natural language name identifying the Template.
Not expected to be globally unique
The offiical version of this profile - for external version specific references
Note that if this is missing, the default version identifier for the profile is the version identifier for the resource that represents the profile itself
Details of the author who accepts responsibility for publishing the profile
Usually an organisation, but may be an individual
Reference to the author to assist a user in finding and communicating with the author
may be a web site, an email address, a telephone number (tel:), etc
natural language description of the Template
A free text natural language description of the Template and it's use

This field can be used for things such as why the profile was written, comments about mis-use, instructions for clinical use and interpretation, literature references, examples from the paper world, etc
A set of terms from external terminologies that may be used to assist with indexing and searching of templates
draft | testing | review | production | withdrawn | superceded
The date that the current value for publicationStatus was applied to the Template
external source of extensions and bindings
Other profiles that define extensions and bindings that are used in this profile
Any resource definitions from these other profiles are not imported
if this describes a bundle, the first resource
If this profile describes a bundle, the first resource in the bundle (usually a Message or a Document)
A constraint statement about what contents a profile may have
The Type of the resource being described
Resource Profile that supplies the constraints
Reference to a resource profile which includes the constraint statement that applies to this resource
The name of this resource constraint statement (to refer to it from other resource constraints)
This field is the target for a resource.profile
Human summary: why describe this resource?
Definition of elements in the resource
The path of the element (see the formal definitions)
Name of constraint for slicing - see above
more specific definition of the element
Definition of the content of the element to provide a more specific definition than that contained for the element in the base resource.
A concise definition that is shown in the concise XML format that summarises profiles
The definition must be consistent with the base definition, but convey the meaning of the element in the particular context of use of the resource
To allow a user to clarify the usageof an element in a particular context
It is easy for a different definition to change the meaning of an element, and this can have nasty downstream consequences. Please be careful when providing definitions
Comments about the use of this element
Comments about the use of the element, including notes about how to use the data properly, exceptions to proper use, etc
The Type of the element can be left blank, in which case the type is inherited from the resource. The type can only be listed in this field if it is an allowed option in the base resource.
A reference to an invariant that may make additional statements about the cardinality in the instance
Xpath condition that must evaluate to true
The rules expressed in the xpath statements should be described in the definition or comments, or in the conditions on the children elements
If the element must be usable
If the element must be understood
Binding - see bindings below (only if coded)
Map element to another set of definitions
Which mapping this is (v2, CDA, openEHR, etc)
Whether this resource is included in the bundle
Whether this resource is included in the bundle, if the profile is specifying a bundle

The reference might be a simple name in the form #[name], which is a reference to another named constraint in a resource - where the resource contains more than one constraint, or a URL which is a reference to a resource Profile
Name (internal ref) or fixed value but not both
if list, whether derived profiles can slice more
identifies the extension in the instance
where the extension can be used in instances
How the context of the extension is interpreted
Definition of the extension and it's content
provide a binding for a name used in an element
The binding name that this profile is defining
human explanation of the binding name
how this binding is mapped to a set of codes
whether the binding is extensible or not, or just suggestive
enumerated codes that are the binding
code to use for this concept
source for the code, if taken from another system
print name. defaults to code if not provided
Text summary of resource profile for human interpretation
Provide either a profile reference or constraints on the resource elements (but not both)
Either a name or a fixed value (but not both) is required
reference must be present and may only be present if binding type is "reference"
concepts must be present and may only be present if binding type is "codelists"
Codes must be unique in the context of a profile
a portion of the name of the resource
a word somewhere in the definition of the resource or the elements in the resource. (Common words - 'and' etc - are often not supported)
name or id of the author
a code in the format uri::code (server may choose to do subsumption)
type of resource that is constrained in the profile
a resource constrained in a profile
an id of another profile referenced in the profile
how this binding is mapped to a set of codes
whether the binding is extensible or not, or just suggestive
The type of context expression applicable
The binding name has an associated URL which is a reference to a Value Set Resource that provides a formal definition of the set of possible codes

The binding name is associated with a simple list of codes, and definitions from some identified code system (SID, URI, OID, UUID). In resource definitions, the system reference may be omitted, and a list of custom codes with definitions supplied (this is for status and workflow fields that applications need to know)
The binding name has an associated URL which refers to some external standard or specification that defines the possible codes
The binding points to a list of concepts defined as part of FHIR itself (see below for possible values)
Only codes in the set are allowed. Profiles can only specify a subset of the defined codes

Codes in the set must be used when their meaning is appropriate. Other codes can be used if no appropriate code is in the set. Profiles can specify a subset of the codes and include other codes that do not overlap in meaning with the codes in the codes in the set
The codes in the set are an example to illustrate the meaning of the field. Other codes may be used, and profiles may choose other sets of codes
The context is all elements matching a particular resource element path
The context is all nodes matching a particular data type element path or all elements referencing a particular primitive data type
The context is all nodes whose mapping to a specified reference model corresponds to a particular mapping structure
The context is a particular extension from a particular profile
The context is a set of other context types
Base Resources defined as profiles (implementation assistance, for derivation and product development)
